ing in two ongoing projects, the Opera Omnia Des. Erasmi published at Amsterdam and The Collected Works of Erasmus published at Toronto.While focusing mainly on these particular editions and translations, the contributors also address such common issues as the problem of authorship, the difficulty of deciphering manuscript sources, the identification of minor historical figures, tracing "ations, and the need to produce idiomatically correct modern translations without diverging from the wording of the original source. In addition, the contributors offer valuable insights into the nature and process of scholarly collaboration and informed comment on the circumstances that allow such endeavours to flourish.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEditingvCongresses. 0aLiterature, Moderny15th and 16th centuriesxTranslationsvCongresses. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh1 aFarge, James K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingdon, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinney, J. Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcconica, James K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMclelland, Joseph C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO\x27donnell, Anne M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRummel, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRummel, Erika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267428840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442674288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/